London Abram Vivian
My last to you was onthe 1p courtt. sence recd yd of 2 & 6 curtt, marmaich suiss is arrived
& the bale n. 70 witl mee sence yeasterday, & sold presentley pout of itt, I finde no raison
to complaine of m. Potters doing, onely the cloth must be prest as much in the bock as
towards the lists, le also sends the bayes in good condition, I have not one. by mee
fram in great want for goods of all sorts, and if Pindar brings not the desired paxcelle
do not knw wat to do, besides I must Istreat you to dispatch Pindar, though wee
I could allow un t0 s5 stivers of choth more, to be gon full, or not full, for in case
le mistayes 14 yett, itt shall be a great preiudice toour trade, I finde the snvoyce
of the 2 bales of bayes so content, by that Pindar is gen you must not be idle, butt
provide toe bayes att least for the ship that will follow tim, assorted from 31, ta 48ƒ,
you may, if you plaise lett y. new man do something now & then in cloth onely, all
hept spaing. I have accepted yd bills for £300- for my acctt & do not quission, butt
that will be sustitient, tbill next month, for then I loye to be a remitter, thee is no
schip now in loading for Rotterdam att Hull, so that all what comes in time must
gea board Bindar, oneles there habbened a vessel for Rrotterdam ready to tayle
I observe what you say about the mary yaglt: I have no pictures for you ready
brutt if I can gett any to yd order itt shall be don, to come by the yaght, if not they
shall be provided for an ether opportunite, whilst I long to know what passes in the
north & nemain

mij last to you was on the 14 curtt to which isserre you, principally recomminding the
providing of the goods shere in specified, & lett the bale of fine cloathes be all fine, thoug
Enstreed of 12 well 15 a 16 p for I lave not one P. by mee, neghet not the pack weites
there inexsprested, for all them I want and the o.N silva mares of 35 a 36 yd as the
gust wee sadd, for the sesuits have refused to take the last & will not lave them, they
beeng to thin . I doubt kent is to tard for in then in, because I lave seen this somme
Rootendael Gad a bale of 5 & of the tune sort, which the sosuis took alfo, & if I must
loose hem, I'll wmitt mij latt bos ef anger, for I can not abide to be ontdon besides
mey will langgs att mee. lett mee lave vere first one bale of wlite cottons from
20 to 22 pence i good, and one bale from 22 to 25, also 16 fises of severall
culleurs some browne and most light lovely drap vul, butt the browne must be
draps to, for all the faises must be draps cullours, the lightest as thes patt. and made
up 2P. in one as for merly, gett also 8 a 10 wanshins whlite bayes, of the green
and gallon streepken to be made up amonghst the prises to be one pack, which
pray dispasch I fust: I wender Ie have non from you, yett to lope that the goods
in the north are read, by this ame for Bindar, & that ie will saile vere first
of which exspect yd advise. observe the frises not toexceed 4:2 2 yd, rather
less, & the swanskins as best you can lave them good white and broad
